value.value: A type of hyperplasia that is characterized by variable thickening of the urinary tract epithelium and a slight papillary growth. The latter is not associated with the presence of fibrovascular cores. There is no evidence of atypia. The relationship between this lesion and papillary urothelial neoplasia is not clear. -- 2003
An infectious process affecting the nail.
A modifier that can be applied to a tumor class describing abnormal tumor histology or morphology. It is an indicator of how quickly a tumor is likely to grow and spread

A term that refers to the cellular differentiation of a malignant cellular infiltrate. A cancer is defined through grades I-IV (or 1-4), or as well, moderately, poorly differentiated or undifferentiated.

label.value: tumor grade X, general grading system

value.value: A morphologic qualifier indicating that a cancerous lesion is well differentiated.
A morphologic qualifier indicating that a cancerous lesion is moderately differentiated.
A morphologic qualifier indicating that a cancerous lesion is poorly differentiated.
A morphologic qualifier indicating that a cancerous lesion is undifferentiated.

label.value: tumor grade 1 or 2, general grading system
tumor grade 2 or 3, general grading system

value.value: A morphologic qualifier indicating that a neoplastic lesion is moderately to poorly differentiated.

label.value: tumor grade 3 or 4, general grading system

value.value: Used to describe tumor samples that exhibit poorly differentiated or undifferentiated cells. They are generally expected to be fast growing and aggressive.
A benign, intermediate, or malignant vascular neoplasm that arises from the bone.
A neuroendocrine neoplasm that involves the duodenum.

A neoplasm with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the appendix. It includes well differentiated neuroendocrine tumors (low and intermediate grade) and poorly differentiated neuroendocrine carcinomas (high grade).

A neoplasm with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the gallbladder. It includes well differentiated neuroendocrine tumors (low and intermediate grade) and poorly differentiated neuroendocrine carcinomas (high grade).

A neoplasm with neuroendocrine differentiation arising from the digestive system. It includes neuroendocrine tumors (well-differentiated endocrine tumors or carcinoid tumors and well differentiated endocrine carcinomas) and neuroendocrine carcinomas (poorly differentiated neuroendocrine carcinomas, small cell carcinomas, and large cell neuroendocrine carcinomas).

label.value: enterochromaffin cell serotonin-producing pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor

value.value: A usually slow-growing, grade 1 pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor that secretes serotonin. When it metastasizes to the liver, it produces the clinical symptoms of the carcinoid syndrome.
Any Adams-Oliver syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the ARHGAP31 gene.
An instance of hidradenitis suppurativa that is caused by an inherited modification of the individual's genome.
A thrombocytosis caused by an underlying condition, such as an infection.
Any primary cutaneous amyloidosis in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the OSMR gene.
Any aortic valve disease in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the NOTCH1 gene.
Any Zimmermann-Laband syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the KCNH1 gene.

label.value: progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions, autosomal dominant 1

value.value: Any autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the POLG gene.
Any tubular aggregate myopathy in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the STIM1 gene.
Any otofaciocervical syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the EYA1 gene.
Any primary pulmonary hypertension in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the BMPR2 gene.
Any Dowling-Degos disease in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the KRT5 gene.
Any singleton-Merten dysplasia in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the IFIH1 gene.
Any familial glucocorticoid deficiency in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the MC2R gene.
Any Brown-Vialetto-van Laere syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the SLC52A3 gene.
Any central areolar choroidal dystrophy in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the GUCY2D gene.
Any Jervell and Lange-Nielsen syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the KCNQ1 gene.
Any tricho-hepato-enteric syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the TTC37 gene.

label.value: cerebellar ataxia, intellectual disability, and dysequilibrium syndrome 1

value.value: Any dysequilibrium syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the VLDLR gene.
